<div class="reflection-block" id="reflect">
    <h2>REFLECTION PROMPTS</h2>
    <p class="ref-intro">Not graded. Write in your own words, 200–400 words each.</p>
    <div class="ref-prompt"><h3>Prompt 1 — When Is the SPC Shift Safe?</h3>
        <p>Identify the conditions under which shifting from 100% unit-level testing to statistical process control is responsible. What process capability metrics (Cpk, defect rate) must be demonstrated first? What is the consequence of making the shift prematurely on a 1,584-satellite programme?</p></div>
    <div class="ref-prompt"><h3>Prompt 2 — COTS Failure Modes</h3>
        <p>Identify three specific scenarios where a COTS-based satellite might fail in a way a rad-hard design would not, and describe how the mass-production reliability model (fleet redundancy, statistical risk acceptance) handles each. Is there a mission type within a LEO constellation that would still require rad-hard components even at 550 km?</p></div>
    <div class="ref-prompt"><h3>Prompt 3 — The Learning Curve as a Competitive Moat</h3>
        <p>The learning curve implies that an incumbent at unit 500 has a cost advantage over a new entrant starting at unit 1. Quantify this disadvantage for a 20% learning rate: at what cumulative production does the new entrant's average cost match the incumbent's marginal cost at unit 500? What does this imply for competitive dynamics in the LEO broadband industry?</p></div>
    <div class="ref-prompt"><h3>Prompt 4 — Mixed Fleet Management</h3>
        <p>A continuous upgrade cycle means multiple satellite generations operate simultaneously. Propose a fleet management strategy that minimises the number of distinct generations operating at once while still enabling regular technology upgrades. Describe the scheduling, transition, and testing requirements your strategy imposes on the ground segment.</p></div>
</div>

