<script>
const canvas=document.getElementById('starsCanvas'),ctx=canvas.getContext('2d');
let stars=[];
function initStars(){stars=[];for(let i=0;i<180;i++)stars.push({x:Math.random()*canvas.width,y:Math.random()*canvas.height,size:Math.random()*1.5+0.4,speed:Math.random()*0.18+0.04,hue:Math.random()*360});}
function resizeCanvas(){canvas.width=window.innerWidth;canvas.height=window.innerHeight;}
resizeCanvas();initStars();window.addEventListener('resize',resizeCanvas);
function animateStars(){ctx.clearRect(0,0,canvas.width,canvas.height);stars.forEach(s=>{s.y-=s.speed;if(s.y<0){s.y=canvas.height;s.x=Math.random()*canvas.width;}ctx.beginPath();ctx.fillStyle=`hsl(${s.hue},80%,80%)`;ctx.arc(s.x,s.y,s.size,0,Math.PI*2);ctx.fill();});requestAnimationFrame(animateStars);}
animateStars();
</script>
<script>
const feedbacks={
    1:{correct:"Correct. The three defining changes are design for manufacturability (co-optimising for production speed and repeatability), automated assembly replacing hand assembly, and statistical process control replacing 100% unit-level acceptance testing.",wrong:"Incorrect. Material cost, satellite size, and orbit regime are not the defining changes. The manufacturing philosophy — DFM, automation, SPC — is the paradigm shift. Longer design lives, more features, and higher EIRP are not characteristics of mass-produced LEO satellites."},
    2:{correct:"Correct. SPC shifts quality assurance from 'test the product' to 'control the process.' A process demonstrably in statistical control produces predictably in-specification units — process excursions, not random defects, cause failures, and these are caught by the monitoring system.",wrong:"Incorrect. No regulation mandates SPC for satellites. Unit testing at high rates is technically possible but prohibitively expensive. SPC does not catch more defects than 100% unit testing — it prevents defects by catching process excursions before they create non-conforming units."},
    3:{correct:"Correct. GEO sits inside the outer Van Allen belt (~15,000–60,000 km) and experiences intense, continuous electron and proton radiation requiring rad-hardened components. LEO below 600 km is largely below the belt and receives only attenuated radiation, making COTS viable with software error correction and system-level redundancy.",wrong:"Incorrect. Component size is not the constraint. Voltage levels are not the primary distinction between rad-hard and COTS. Solar arrays do not shield internal electronics from radiation — the satellite interior is not significantly shielded by the panels."},
    4:{correct:"Correct. C_N = C₁ × N^(log(0.80)/log(2)) = C₁ × 100^(−0.322) ≈ 0.46 × C₁. A 20% learning rate means cost falls 20% each time cumulative production doubles; six to seven doublings from unit 1 to unit 100 reduces cost to approximately 46%.",wrong:"Incorrect. 80% is the cost after the first doubling (the 2nd unit costs 80% of the 1st at a 20% learning rate). 20% would require a ~35% learning rate. 1% would require an implausibly aggressive learning rate well beyond any documented aerospace programme."},
    5:{correct:"Correct. A 5-year design life requires replacing ~317 satellites per year on a 1,584-satellite fleet — manageable with established production rates. Short design lives enable rapid technology refresh on every generation, and propellant budgets remain modest compared to a 15-year design that must also correct inclination drift.",wrong:"Incorrect. Technology can achieve longer LEO lifetimes — the binding factors are propellant budget and business case, not technical capability. No regulator mandates a 5-year maximum design life. Satellite mass is driven primarily by propulsion system size, not directly by design life."},
    6:{correct:"Correct. Traditional harness wiring is the most labour-intensive part of spacecraft integration. A GEO satellite may have 15,000 unique wire runs taking months of manual work. Pre-wired looms manufactured off-satellite and installed as plug-and-play assemblies reduce electrical assembly from months to days.",wrong:"Incorrect. EMC is managed through shielding and routing, not primarily through loom pre-wiring. On-orbit electrical repair is not a feature of LEO broadband satellites. Loom assemblies are typically similar in mass to equivalent point-to-point runs."},
    7:{correct:"Correct. Satellite unit cost falls with cumulative production (satellite learning curve). Launch cost per kilogram also falls with booster reuse maturity and cumulative launches (launch learning curve). Both apply simultaneously and compound the total cost reduction across the programme life.",wrong:"Incorrect. Total deployment cost falls substantially as both curves apply — it is not constant. The curves add rather than cancel. Both satellite and launch learning curves apply to the same programme simultaneously."},
    8:{correct:"Correct. When new satellite generations enter service before all old-generation units have retired, the operational fleet contains hardware with different capabilities, software versions, and failure modes. Managing this mixed fleet adds scheduling complexity, spare parts fragmentation, and ground software testing burden.",wrong:"Incorrect. Mass growth per generation is a real concern but not the primary upgrade cycle risk. Regulatory approval timelines for incremental design changes are typically accelerated. Customer service is abstracted through the network layer, hiding hardware generation from end users."},
    9:{correct:"Correct. 15 launches × 53 sats = 795 sats/year ÷ 365 days ≈ 2.2 sats/day, or one satellite every ~11 hours. A 2-station production line with an 11-hour cycle time matches this rate precisely.",wrong:"Incorrect. 1/day gives only 365/year, leaving launch capacity idle. 10/day far exceeds the launch constraint — satellites would accumulate in storage. 53/day equals one full Falcon 9 load per day, far beyond any current or planned production capability."},
    10:{correct:"Correct. A 1% annual failure rate on 1,584 satellites is ~16 satellites — a small fractional coverage impact. The constellation is the system; redundancy is at the fleet level, not the unit level. This allows a relaxed unit reliability specification and lower unit cost, which is the economic rationale for the mass-production model.",wrong:"Incorrect. The cost of each satellite (~$400k) is precisely high enough that the economics of failures do matter — the fleet redundancy model is the justification, not cost insignificance. LEO satellites cannot be repaired after launch. Insurance is a financial tool, not the technical justification for a lower reliability target."}
};
let answered={};
document.querySelectorAll('.quiz-opt').forEach(btn=>{
    btn.addEventListener('click',function(){
        const q=this.dataset.q;
        if(answered[q]!==undefined)return;
        const correct=this.dataset.correct==='true';
        answered[q]=correct;
        document.querySelectorAll(`.quiz-opt[data-q="${q}"]`).forEach(b=>{b.disabled=true;if(b.dataset.correct==='true')b.classList.add('correct');});
        if(!correct)this.classList.add('wrong');
        const fb=document.getElementById(`fb${q}`);
        fb.textContent=(correct?'✓ ':'✗ ')+feedbacks[q][correct?'correct':'wrong'];
        fb.style.color=correct?'#39ff14':'#ff004f';
        if(Object.keys(answered).length===10){
            const total=Object.values(answered).filter(Boolean).length;
            const el=document.getElementById('quizScore');
            el.style.display='block';
            const pct=Math.round(total/10*100);
            el.textContent=`SCORE: ${total} / 10 (${pct}%) — ${pct===100?'PERFECT.':pct>=80?'STRONG. REVIEW ANY MISSES.':pct>=60?'ADEQUATE. REVISIT WEAK SECTIONS.':'REVISIT MODULE 3 BEFORE PROCEEDING TO M4.'}`;
        }
    });
});
</script>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@supabase/supabase-js@2"></script>
<script src="supabase.js"></script>
<script src="user_progress.js"></script>
<script>
const LESSON_ID='m3-6';
(function(){
    function bounceToLogin(r){console.error("Auth guard:",r);window.location.replace("index.html");}
    async function init(){
        if(typeof client==="undefined"||!client||!client.auth)return bounceToLogin("Supabase client not loaded");
        let session=null;
        try{({data:{session}}=await client.auth.getSession());}
        catch(e){return bounceToLogin("getSession threw: "+e.message);}
        if(!session){window.location.replace("index.html");return;}
        const btn=document.getElementById('completeBtn'),msg=document.getElementById('completeMsg');
        function setDone(done){
            if(done){btn.textContent='✓ COMPLETE — CLICK TO UNDO';btn.classList.add('done');btn.style.cssText='border-color:#39ff14;color:#39ff14;background:rgba(57,255,20,0.1);cursor:pointer;opacity:1;';msg.style.color='#39ff14';msg.textContent='Module 3 complete. Proceed to M4.';}
            else{btn.textContent='MARK LESSON COMPLETE';btn.classList.remove('done');btn.style.cssText='';msg.style.color='#ffffff55';msg.textContent='Not yet marked complete.';}
        }
        let mastered=[];
        try{mastered=await getMasteredSections();}catch(e){console.error(e);}
        setDone(mastered.includes(LESSON_ID));
        btn.addEventListener('click',async()=>{
            const isDone=btn.classList.contains('done');
            msg.style.color='#00d9ff';msg.textContent='Saving...';
            const ok=await upsertSection(LESSON_ID,!isDone);
            if(ok){setDone(!isDone);}else{msg.style.color='#ff004f';msg.textContent='Error saving. Try again.';}
        });
        const btt=document.getElementById('backToTop');
        window.addEventListener('scroll',()=>{btt.classList.toggle('visible',window.scrollY>400);});
        btt.addEventListener('click',()=>window.scrollTo({top:0,behavior:'smooth'}));
    }
    if(document.readyState==="loading")document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded",init);
    else init();
})();
</script>
</body>
</html>
